You're storing Playwright expressions, not reusable locator definitions
What your code currently does

Inside BrowserActionImpl:

await this.captureAndStore(
  finalLocator,
  elementName,
  finalLocator.toString()
);

Suppose:

this.userName = page.locator('#userNameField');

Then:

finalLocator.toString()

returns something similar to:

locator('#userNameField')

Likewise:

page.getByPlaceholder('Current Address')

becomes:

getByPlaceholder('Current Address')

and:

page.getByRole('button', { name: 'Submit Order' })

becomes:

getByRole('button', { name: 'Submit Order' })
Why this is a problem

You later load that value from the DB:

locator('#userNameField')

and try to validate it.

Most frameworks then do:

page.locator(storedLocator)

which becomes:

page.locator(
  "locator('#userNameField')"
);

Playwright thinks:

locator('#userNameField')

is CSS.

But it isn't.

So Playwright throws:

Unexpected token "locator("

Exactly what your logs show.

Think of it this way
This is executable code
page.getByLabel('Username')
This is data
{
  "type": "label",
  "value": "Username"
}

Your DB should store data.

Not executable Playwright snippets.

Current Flow
Locator
   ↓
toString()
   ↓
"getByLabel('Username')"
   ↓
DB
   ↓
page.locator("getByLabel('Username')")
   ↓
BOOM
Correct Flow
Locator
   ↓
Extract metadata
   ↓
{
  type: "label",
  value: "Username"
}
   ↓
DB
   ↓
Rebuild locator
   ↓
page.getByLabel("Username")
Proper fix

Instead of:

primaryLocator: finalLocator.toString()

Store:

primaryLocator: {
  strategy: 'css',
  value: '#userNameField'
}

or:

primaryLocator: {
  strategy: 'label',
  value: 'Current address'
}
Example

Current DB:

{
  "primary_locator": "getByPlaceholder('Current Address')"
}

Better:

{
  "primary_locator": {
    "strategy": "placeholder",
    "value": "Current Address"
  }
}

Then rebuilding is trivial:

switch(strategy) {
  case 'placeholder':
    return page.getByPlaceholder(value);

  case 'label':
    return page.getByLabel(value);

  case 'css':
    return page.locator(value);

  case 'xpath':
    return page.locator(`xpath=${value}`);
}
Bug #2 — Your validator assumes every locator is CSS

This one is causing the address failure.

Evidence from logs

AI returned:

getByLabel('Current address', { exact: true })

This locator is correct.

Let's prove it.

Your HTML:

<label for="addressField">
  Current address
</label>

<textarea
  id="addressField"
  placeholder="Address (updated)">
</textarea>

Playwright:

page.getByLabel('Current address')

will absolutely find that textarea.

Yet your framework says
Locator validation failed
Unsupported token "{"

Why?

Because somewhere you're doing:

page.locator(
  "getByLabel('Current address', { exact: true })"
)
What Playwright sees
getByLabel('Current address', { exact: true })

CSS parser:

WHAT IS THIS???

and throws:

Unsupported token "{"
Why phone succeeded

AI returned:

getByLabel('Phone')

No braces.

Your parser may have special-cased it accidentally.

Or stripped arguments.

Or converted it differently.

Why address failed

Address locator contains:

{ exact: true }

which CSS parser cannot understand.

So validation fails before Playwright ever tries the locator.

How to fix Bug #2 properly

Create a single function:

function buildLocator(
  page: Page,
  strategy: string,
  value: string
): Locator

Example:

function buildLocator(
  page: Page,
  strategy: string,
  value: string
): Locator {

  switch(strategy) {

    case 'css':
      return page.locator(value);

    case 'xpath':
      return page.locator(`xpath=${value}`);

    case 'label':
      return page.getByLabel(value);

    case 'placeholder':
      return page.getByPlaceholder(value);

    case 'role':
      return page.getByRole(value as any);

    case 'testId':
      return page.getByTestId(value);

    default:
      return page.locator(value);
  }
}
Even better

Your AI should NOT return:

getByLabel('Current address', { exact: true })

as raw text.

It should return structured JSON:

{
  "strategy": "label",
  "value": "Current address",
  "exact": true
}

Then:

page.getByLabel(
  result.value,
  { exact: result.exact }
)

No parsing required.

No regex required.

No brittle string manipulation.

What I would change immediately
Fix #1

Replace:

finalLocator.toString()

with a structured locator model.

Never store Playwright expressions in DB.

Fix #2

Stop validating via:

page.locator(locatorString)

Build the locator according to its strategy.

Result

After those two fixes, your current failing case:

LocatorLabPage_address

would likely become:

